Yeah—Death Note is a great reference. It’s basically a study in how a frame of belief (Light’s “justice”) can get so tight and self-reinforcing that it starts to overwrite feedback from reality. That’s the cautionary edge of powerful framing.

Your sights analogy works well too. I’d just tune it a bit:

* Rear sight (your frame) → your model, expectations, biases
* Front sight (the target / reality) → what’s actually there, signals coming back
* Alignment → action based on how well those two line up

The important part is the loop:

Align → act → observe impact → re-align

That last step—re-alignment from feedback—is what keeps it grounded and prevents drift into a self-sealed frame (the Death Note trap).

⸻

Practical way to run it

Before action

* What am I assuming here? (rear sight)
* What evidence am I using? (front sight)

During

* Keep the “front sight” in focus: what’s actually happening right now?

After

* What changed?
* Did my model predict that?
* What do I update?

If the frame stops updating, you start “shooting with last week’s sights.”

⸻

A simple guardrail

* Look for disconfirming evidence on purpose
* Get at least one outside perspective
* Prefer small, reversible tests over big, one-way bets

⸻

Tie back to what you’re building

For Wild Hawg:

* Frame: “daily energy, not a pre-workout”
* Reality check: do people actually use it daily? does messaging change behavior?
* Loop: test ads → measure → adjust visuals/language

⸻

Distilled

Your frame aims. Reality confirms. Feedback refines.

That’s how you keep precision without getting lost in your own model.